<dl id="n54129n"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54129n">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54129n"> 129(n)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> 1 = moon, 2 eye 3 fire / 0 = sky 32 teeth <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54129n"><li>FW 271.f1 </li><li><a href="../../flex/ln/lexln.htm#n54129n">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ln/l39ln.htm#n54129n">1939</a> <a href="../../flex/lc/lexlc.htm#f052">&nbsp;fn052</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54129n">MS BL 47478-334</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:313 <a name="lad13" href="../../FF/fdra/lda.htm#lcd13">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lc/lcd13.htm#n54129n">Draft: II.2&sect;3.13</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">2. Au lieu d&apos;&eacute;crire un nombre en chiffres, les auteurs de trait&eacute;s techniques pr&eacute;f&egrave;rent souvent nommer ses chiffres successivement, en commen&ccedil;ant par les unit&eacute;s (au rebours de l&apos;&eacute;criture), au moyen d&apos;expressions m&eacute;taphoriques. C&apos;est ainsi que 1320 se dira: &laquo;<i>infini</i> (= 0), <mark><i>&oelig;il</i> (= 2)</mark>, <mark><i>feu</i> (= 3</mark>, car chaque ma&icirc;tre de maison entretient trois feux), <mark>lune (=1)</mark>&raquo;, ou encore: &laquo;<mark>ciel</mark> (= 0), dent (= 32), as (= 1, aux d&eacute;s)&raquo;. Ici, ce sont les mots &laquo;infini&raquo; ou &laquo;ciel&raquo; qui nous avertissent que les noms suivants, &laquo;<mark>&oelig;il</mark>&raquo; ou &laquo;<mark>dent</mark>&raquo;, signifieront des dizaines, c&apos;est-&agrave;-dire 20 ou 320, et non pas 2 ou <mark>32</mark>. <br><font color="green">[Instead of writing a number in numbers, the authors of technical treatises often prefer to name its numbers successively, starting with the units (in reverse of writing), using metaphorical expressions. This is how 1320 will say: "infinite (= 0), eye (= 2), fire (= 3, because each master of the house maintains three fires), moon (= 1)", or: "sky (= 0), tooth (= 32), ace (= 1, dice)". Here, it is the words "infinite" or "sky" which warn us that the following names, "eye" or "tooth", will mean tens, that is to say 20 or 320, and not 2 or 32.]</font> <small> Ren&eacute; Daumal, <a name="RDLP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RDLP"><cite title="source">Les pouvoirs de la parole</cite></a> (1938) [82]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
